{
  "texts": [
    "However, none of these results provides any information on the magnitude of λ (nor on its dependence on the initial datum and on the physical quantities appearing in the problem) since they rely on the non-constructive argument that the essential spectrum of the coercive part of L M∞ is preserved under the action of the remaining compact component, thanks to Weyl's theorem [41].The construction of a quantitative theory of convergence to equilibrium for solutions to the Boltzmann equation ( 1) that are already close to a steady state, in this linearized setting, translates into the derivation of explicit estimates for the spectral gap λ and is known to constitute a first fundamental step for determining the effective relaxation rates in the full nonlinear case [43], when combined with far-from-equilibrium quantitative entropy dissipation estimates [30].",
    "The first outcomes in this sense were established in the case of Maxwell molecules via an explicit diagonalization of the linearized Boltzmann operator [12,51].",
    "In more recent years, systematic derivations of explicit hypocoercivity estimates for the linearized collision operator have been obtained for general cutoff and non-cutoff collision kernels [4,42,45], finally leading to the first quantitative results on the relaxation to equilibrium in the full nonhomogeneous setting [43,44].",
    "Notice that these derivations have also opened the way to the recovery of explicit convergence rates toward the hydrodynamic regimes of the Boltzmann equation, applied in combination with the energy method [39] or the hypocoercive approach [20].We are interested here in examining this question in the framework of the kinetic theory of multicomponent reacting gases [2,23,32,33,34,38,46,47].",
    "Without going into too much details, we consider a mixture of 4 different species S i, 1≤ i ≤ 4, whose distribution function F = (F 1,..., F 4) solves, on R + × T 3 × R 3, the Boltzmann-like equation (3) ∂ t F + v • ∇ x F = Q(F, F),where the Boltzmann operator Q = Q EL + Q CH splits into an inert part Q EL modeling microscopic elastic binary collisions between the particles and a reactive term Q CH describing reversible bimolecular chemical reactions of the form S 1 + S 2 ⇋ S 3 + S 4, with chemical binding energy E 34 12."
  ]
}